\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Qualitative case study of baseline and FDIL on representative Intentonomy samples. In the first row, the baseline predicts an incorrect semantic alternative, whereas FDIL removes that distractor by leveraging counterfactual evidence in the rationale and yields the correct intent decision. In the second row, FDIL makes an error, but the annotated soft label itself has only 0.33 agreement, indicating substantial ambiguity; under such weak supervision, the alternative prediction made by FDIL remains semantically plausible rather than arbitrarily wrong.}}{27}{}\protected@file@percent }
